.NET 8+ (including .NET 10) ships with a built-in abstraction for this: **`System.TimeProvider`**. No need to create your own.

**1. Inject `TimeProvider` into your class:**

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(TimeProvider timeProvider)
{
    public Report Generate()
    {
        var now = timeProvider.GetUtcNow(); // instead of DateTime.UtcNow
        // ...
    }
}
```

**2. In production (DI registration):**

```csharp
services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

**3. In tests, use `FakeTimeProvider`:**

```
dotnet add <TestProject> package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
```

```csharp
var fake = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 9, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var generator = new ReportGenerator(fake);

var report = generator.Generate();

Assert.Equal(new DateTime(2026, 1, 15, 9, 0, 0), report.GeneratedAt);

// You can also advance time:
fake.Advance(TimeSpan.FromHours(1));
```

This gives you fully deterministic tests with no custom abstractions needed.
